If you like here is the code I use to accept invites.
    if(message.content.startswith('::join')):
        if message.author.id in somedict['Users']:
            await client.send_message(message.channel, message.author.mention + " Due to Continuous abuse you have been Bot Banned.")
        else:
            code = message.content[len("::join "):].strip()
            url = code
            if code.rfind('https://discord.gg/') == -1:
                try:
                    invite = 'https://discord.gg/' + code
                    await client.accept_invite(invite)
                    await client.send_message(message.channel, 'Successfully Joined the server.')
                except discord.errors.NotFound:
                    await client.send_message(message.channel, 'Sorry, You did not specify a code or a Valid URL to Join a Server.')
            else:
                if url.rfind('https://discord.gg/') != -1:
                    try:
                        code = url[len("https://discord.gg/"):].strip()
                        invite = 'https://discord.gg/' + code
                        await client.accept_invite(invite)
                        await client.send_message(message.channel, 'Successfully Joined the server.')
                    except discord.errors.NotFound:
                        await client.send_message(message.channel, 'Sorry, You did not specify a code or a Valid URL to Join a Server.')

@macisamuele good points, and as we've discussed I'm not sure about what the best approach overall is. Earlier on I used a BravadoTimeoutError; the problem with not using an exception from `exceptions_to_catch` is that the `fallback_result` function is not guaranteed to be able to handle that type of exception.

This PR gives users some control over which exception is going to be thrown in the `force` case, although I'll admit it's quite unintuitive and doesn't cover all cases.

If we're ok with introducing this new custom exception type then I'll go ahead and change this PR accordingly - users can then adapt their callback functions to treat it any way they want to.

would it be better to explicitly define a `getAlertWithMaximumLength()` function with local scope? This might add to the readability:

```javascript
            const getMaximumAlertLength = alertList => Math.max(...alertList.map(alert => alert.title.length));

            const formatAlert = function (alert, alertList) {
                return _.padStart(alert.amount_pct.toFixed(0), 3) + '%  ' +
                (alert.title.padEnd(getMaximumAlertLength(alertList) + 5)) +
                displayNumberFilter(alert.prev_value) + ' -> ' + displayNumberFilter(alert.new_value);
```

